{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181017200927|864528005","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Dan_Donovan_(politician)","to":"Dan Donovan (politician)"}],"pages":{"27446608":{"pageid":27446608,"ns":0,"title":"Dan Donovan (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-20T19:09:55Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Dan Donovan\n|image        = Dan Donovan official photo.jpg\n|state        = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district     = {{ushr|NY|11|11th}}\n|term_start   = May 5, 2015\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Michael Grimm (politician)|Michael Grimm]]\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[District Attorney of Richmond County (New York)|District Attorney of Richmond County]]\n|term_start1  = January 1, 2004\n|term_end1    = May 5, 2015\n|predecessor1 = [[William L. Murphy]]\n|successor1   = [[Michael McMahon]]\n|office2      = [[Borough president#Richmond/Staten Island Borough Presidents|Deputy Borough President of Staten Island]]\n|president2   = [[James Molinaro]]\n|term_start2  = January 1, 2002\n|term_end2    = December 31, 2003\n|predecessor2 = [[James Molinaro]]\n|successor2   = [[Edward Burke (Staten Island)|Edward Burke]]\n|birth_name   = Daniel Michael Donovan Jr.\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|11|6}}\n|birth_place  = [[Staten Island, New York|Staten Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican (United States)|Republican]]\n|education    = [[St. John's University (New York City)|St. John's University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Fordham University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website      = {{url|donovan.house.gov|House website}}\n|signature    = Daniel Donovan signature.png\n}}\n'''Daniel Michael Donovan Jr.''' (born November 6, 1956) is an American attorney, former prosecutor, and politician. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], he is currently the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for [[New York's 11th congressional district]], first elected in a May 2015 special election. The district includes all of [[Staten Island]], as well as portions of southwest [[Brooklyn]]. He is the only Republican representing a significant portion of [[New York City]] in Congress.\n\n==Early life and career==\nDonovan was born into a [[working-class]] [[Roman Catholic]] family in [[Staten Island, New York]] in 1956. His [[Irish-American]] father, Daniel Michael Donovan, was a [[longshoreman]] and lifelong Democrat; his [[Polish-American]] mother, Katherine Bolewicz Donovan, was a [[garment worker]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Geoffrey|url=http://nymag.com/news/intelligencer/encounter/68321|title=110 Minutes With Republican Attorney General Candidate Dan Donovan|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=September 19, 2010|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.feetintwoworlds.org/2010/10/12/half-polish-catholic-ag-candidate-wants-ny-polish-community-to-know-his-background|title=Half-Polish & Catholic AG candidate wants NY Polish community to know his background|accessdate=2011-04-02|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101221020114/http://news.feetintwoworlds.org/2010/10/12/half-polish-catholic-ag-candidate-wants-ny-polish-community-to-know-his-background|archivedate=December 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe was raised in the [[Tompkinsville, Staten Island|Tompkinsville]] section of the borough.<ref name=\"dandonovan1\">{{cite web|title=Meet Dan Donovan|publisher=Donovan New York Attorney General|url=http://www.dandonovan.org/meet_dan.php|accessdate=June 4, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100710132803/http://www.dandonovan.org/meet_dan.php|archivedate=July 10, 2010}}</ref> He attended [[Monsignor Farrell High School]], an all-boys Catholic school, graduating in 1974. He went to study Criminal Justice at [[St. John's University (New York)|St. John's University]]. After graduating from there he attended [[Fordham University School of Law]], earning his [[juris doctor]] in 1988.<ref name=\"dandonovan1\"/>\n\nIn 1989, Donovan became an Assistant District Attorney in the office of [[Robert M. Morgenthau]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rcda.nyc.gov/meet.html|title=Richmond County District Attorneys Office|publisher=Rcda.nyc.gov|date=January 1, 2004|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> He served in the office of the [[New York County District Attorney]] under Morgenthau until 1996. Later that year Donovan became Chief of Staff to then Staten Island [[Borough President]] [[Guy V. Molinari]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://brooklyn.ny1.com/content/news_beats/politics/118626/da-donovan-set-to-announce-ag-run/?ap=1&MP4|title=DA Donovan Set To Announce AG Run|publisher=ny1.com|accessdate=2017-05-04|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714215917/http://brooklyn.ny1.com/content/news_beats/politics/118626/da-donovan-set-to-announce-ag-run/?ap=1&MP4|archivedate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> He remained in that position until 2002 when he was sworn in as Deputy Borough President of Staten Island; he had been appointed by his immediate predecessor and the then new Borough President [[James Molinaro]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n==Richmond County District Attorney==\nIn 2003, twenty-year incumbent Democrat [[William L. Murphy]] decided not to seek re-election. Donovan announced his intention to run to succeed him. In the election he faced Chief Assistant District Attorney David Lehr and won with over 53% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vote.nyc.ny.us/results.html|title=Board of Elections in the City of New York|publisher=Vote.nyc.ny.us|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> A key part of his platform was to start the county's first witness protection program, and his office led the city's prosecutors with the highest felony conviction rate in many of the years since he took office.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2010/05/swimming_upstream_in_bid_for_s.html|title=Daniel Donovan swimming upstream in bid for state office|newspaper=Staten Island Advance|date=May 30, 2010|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was re-elected in 2007 with over 68% of the vote, defeating local Democratic attorney Michael Ryan<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2007/11/07/2007-11-07_staten_island_da_daniel_donovan_survives.html|title=Staten Island DA Donovan survives challenge|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 7, 2007|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> despite a last minute endorsement for his rival by longtime friend and mentor [[Staten Island]] [[Borough President]] [[James Molinaro]]; Molinaro was angered that Donovan had referred his grandson's case to a special prosecutor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/03/nyregion/03staten.html?ref=james_p_molinaro|title=S.I. Borough President Backs Ex-Aide's Rival|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDonovan's tenure as DA has seen several high-profile cases, including the second conviction of Andre Rand, long suspected in a string of kidnappings on Staten Island. In 2010, famed rapper [[Method Man]] pleaded guilty to attempted tax evasion and was forced to pay about $106,000 in restitution and penalties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/06/dan-donovan-versus-method-man.html|accessdate=July 13, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703024555/http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/06/dan-donovan-versus-method-man.html|archivedate=July 3, 2010|title=Dan Donovan versus Method Man}}</ref>\n\n===Eric Garner case===\nDonovan became the focus of a national controversy surrounding the death of [[Eric Garner]] in 2014<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/24/eric-garner-vinnie-gentile-daniel-donovan-race-baiting_n_6933660.html|title=Eric Garner Prosecutor Accused Of 'Doubling Down On Race-Baiting' In Congressional Campaign|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|accessdate=July 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/12/04/meet-dan-donovan-the-prosecutor-who-let-eric-garner-s-killer-walk.html|title=Meet Dan Donovan, the Prosecutor Who Let Eric Garner's Killer Walk|newspaper=[[The Daily Beast]]|accessdate=July 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/23/nyregion/daniel-donovan-gets-a-wary-welcome-to-congress-after-eric-garner-case.html?_r=0|title=Daniel Donovan Gets Wary Welcome to Congress After Eric Garner Case|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/politics/politicsnow/la-pn-dan-donovan-congress-20150505-story.html|title=Dan Donovan, prosecutor in Eric Garner death case, wins House seat|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=July 8, 2015}}</ref> \nwhen a [[Richmond County, New York]] grand jury declined to indict Daniel Pantaleo, the officer whose choke hold the medical examiner determined was instrumental in Garner's death, on any charges. The medical examiner had ruled Garner's death a homicide. After considering the medical examiner's findings that Garner was killed by \"compression of neck (choke hold), compression of chest and prone positioning during physical restraint by police\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/05/opinion/eric-garner-daniel-pantaleo-and-lethal-police-tactics.html|title=It Wasn't Just the Chokehold|date=December 5, 2014|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nDonovan's office declared \"it is appropriate to present evidence regarding circumstances of his death to a Richmond County Grand Jury.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2014/08/19/grand-jury-will-hear-evidence-on-eric-garners-death|title=Federal grand jury hears evidence in Eric Garner chokehold case|publisher=Village Voice|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDonovan asked the grand jury to consider whether there was \"probable cause\" for manslaughter and criminally negligent homicide, but did not bring forward reckless endangerment charges.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nyc-crime/nypd-commissioner-bill-bratton-defends-de-blasio-article-1.2034559|title=DA didn't ask for reckless endangerment in Eric Garner case|newspaper=New York Daily News|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref> After two months, the grand jury brought forward no indictment. Donovan's office strenuously opposed releasing the trial proceedings citing New York confidentiality laws despite being pressured by activists and lawmakers to release the records.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/petition-pressure-dan-donovan-release-garner-records-blog-entry-1.2093763|title=Petition pressure on Dan Donovan to release Garner records|newspaper=New York Daily News|accessdate=November 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==2010 New York Attorney General campaign==\nOn May 17, 2010, Donovan, a registered Republican, announced his candidacy for the [[New York attorney general election, 2010]], becoming the front runner for his party's nomination.<ref>Wrobleski, Tom (May 17, 2010). [http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2010/05/staten_island_da_daniel_donova.html Staten Island D.A. Daniel Donovan announces A.G. run, vows to fight corruption in Albany]. ''Staten Island Advance''. Retrieved May 22, 2010.</ref> However, Bob Antonacci, [[Onondaga County]] [[Comptroller]], announced his intention run for Attorney General.<ref>Mariani, Tom (May 17, 2010). [http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2010/05/staten_island_da_to_declare_at.html Staten Island DA Daniel Donovan to declare attorney general candidacy in Syracuse], ''The Post-Standard''; retrieved July 13, 2010.</ref>\n\nAntonacci stepped aside and endorsed Donovan after earning forty percent of the vote at the 2010 Republican State Convention.<ref>Knauss, Tim (June 2, 2010). [http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2010/06/onondaga_comptroller_robert_an.html Staten Island DA Daniel Donovan to declare attorney general candidacy in Syracuse], ''The Post-Standard''; retrieved July 13, 2010.</ref> With a sixty percent win of the delegates at the convention and no primary opponent, Donovan became the presumptive nominee of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nygop.org/page/new-york-state-republicans-nominate-dan-donovan-as-their-candidate-for-attorney-general|accessdate=September 23, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100809142333/http://www.nygop.org/page/new-york-state-republicans-nominate-dan-donovan-as-their-candidate-for-attorney-general|archivedate=August 9, 2010|title=NYS Republicans nominate Dan Donovan as their candidate for Attorney General}}; retrieved July 13, 2010.</ref>\n\nOne week earlier, he had received the endorsement of the [[Conservative Party of New York]] but was defeated on November 2 by Democrat [[Eric Schneiderman]].<ref>Hornak, Robert (May 31, 2010). [http://www.urbanelephants.com/index.php/component/content/article/64/2688-state-conservative-party-meets-endorse-jay-townend-joe-dioguardi-for-senate-dan-donovan-for-attorney-general-harry-wilson-for-comptroller-and-surprise-rick-lazio-for-governor.html State Conservative Party Meets: Endorse Townsend, DioGuardi, Donovan, Wilson and (Surprise!) Rick Lazio] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201192428/http://www.urbanelephants.com/index.php/component/content/article/64/2688-state-conservative-party-meets-endorse-jay-townend-joe-dioguardi-for-senate-dan-donovan-for-attorney-general-harry-wilson-for-comptroller-and-surprise-rick-lazio-for-governor.html|date=December 1, 2010}}; retrieved July 13, 2010.</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n{{See also|New York's 11th congressional district special election, 2015}}\nDonovan was selected as the Republican candidate for [[New York's 11th congressional district]] after the resignation of [[Michael Grimm (politician)|Michael Grimm]]. He defeated the Democrat, [[Vincent J. Gentile]], and the Green Party candidate, James Lane, in the [[New York's 11th congressional district special election, 2015|May 2015 special election]].<ref name=\"advancevictory\">Shapiro, Rachel (May 5, 2015). [http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2015/05/dan_donovan_wins_race_is_elect.html#incart_river Staten Island special election 2015: Dan Donovan wins Congress seat]. ''Staten Island Advance''; retrieved May 5, 2015.</ref> Donovan was elected May 5, 2015 and sworn into office on May 12, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Katinas|first1=Paula|title=Donovan To Be Sworn Into Office May 12|url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2015/5/11/donovan-be-sworn-office-may-12|date=May 11, 2015|newspaper=[[Brooklyn Eagle]]|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Donovan faced Democrat [[Richard Reichard]] in his first re-election bid.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2016/03/democrat_richard_reichard_to_c.html|title=Democrat Richard Reichard to challenge Rep. Dan Donovan|newspaper=Staten Island Advance|access-date=2016-10-26}}</ref> Donovan was re-elected with 56.8% of the vote.\n\nIn 2018, Donovan faced a primary challenge from former Rep. [[Michael Grimm (politician)|Michael Grimm]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/06/14/michael-grimm-dan-donovan-primary-pardon-645617|title=Grimm lobs grenade into GOP primary with Trump pardon claim|work=POLITICO|access-date=2018-06-15|language=en}}</ref> During the primary campaign, Grimm accused Donovan of having tried to entice Grimm to drop out of the race by offering to lobby Trump to pardon Grimm.<ref name=\":2\" /> Grimm pleaded guilty to federal tax evasion charges in 2014 and spent several months in prison.<ref name=\":2\" /> During the primary, both candidates emphasized their loyalty to Trump, seeking to \"out-Trump each other,\" according to the ''Washington Post.''<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/should-a-felon-serve-in-the-house-thats-the-question-for-staten-island-republicans/2018/06/22/4f928a30-733d-11e8-b4b7-308400242c2e_story.html|title=Should a felon serve in the House? That\u2019s the question for Staten Island Republicans.|last=Weigel|first=David|date=2018-06-23|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-06-24|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> In the 2018 general election Donovan is facing [[Max Rose (politician)|Max Rose]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/06/26/us/elections/results-new-york-primary-elections.html|title=New York Primary Election Results|last=Almukhtar|first=Sarah|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations|Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere|Subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications|Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications]] (Chairman)\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Cybersecurity, Infrastructure Protection, and Security Technologies|Subcommittee on Cybersecurity, Infrastructure Protection, and Security Technologies]]\n\nDonovan is a member of the moderate [[Republican Main Street Partnership]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> the [[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|format=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|date=|accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref> and the [[Climate Solutions Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=90 Current Climate Solutions Caucus Members|author=|url=https://citizensclimatelobby.org/climate-solutions-caucus/|format=|publisher=Citizen\u00b4s Climate Lobby |date=|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Town halls===\n\nDonovan has faced a number of protests from constituents seeking town hall meetings. After being heckled at public events, he has instead held telephone phone halls over \"fears that any large-scale town hall will devolve into mayhem.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.brooklyndaily.com/stories/2017/8/br-protest-at-dan-donovan-office-2017-02-24-bk.html|title=Protestors slam Rep. Donovan outside Dyker office|work=Brooklyn Daily|access-date=2017-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/index.ssf/2017/02/concerned_staten_islanders_ral.html|title=Islanders rally at Donovan's office, demand to be heard on health care|work=Staten Island Advance|access-date=2017-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bklyner.com/wheres-plan-dan-southern-brooklyn-residents-protest-donovans-vote-aca|title='Where's The Plan, Dan?' Southern Brooklynites Protest Donovan's Stance Against ACA|last=Miller|first=Carly|date=2017-02-21|work=bklyner.com|access-date=2017-03-05}}</ref>\n\nConstituents have organized a variety of town halls to which Donovan has been invited. He has not attended, saying that to avoid disruptions, he only holds town halls over the phone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2017/02/23/town-hall-meeting-on-staten-island-addresses-concerns-over-health-care.html|title=Town Hall on Staten Island Addresses Concerns Over Health Care|work=TWC News|access-date=2017-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newyork.peoplesclimate.org/event/sidewalk-sit-in-at-donovan-tele-town-hall/2017-02-16/|title=Sidewalk Sit-in at Donovan Tele-town Hall|work=New York|access-date=2017-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bklyner.com/donovan-host-tele-town-hall-bay-ridge-activists-host-live-town-hall/|title=Donovan To Host Tele-Town Hall; Bay Ridge Activists Host Live Town Hall|first=Carly|last=Miller|date=April 12, 2017|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"brooklyneagle.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2017/4/21/fight-back-bay-ridge-leaders-hope-town-hall-springboard|title=Fight Back Bay Ridge leaders hope town hall is springboard|newspaper=Brooklyn Eagle|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://brooklynreporter.com/story/donovan-refuses-invitation-to-upcoming-constituent-organized-town-hall-in-bay-ridge|title=Donovan refuses invitation to upcoming constituent-organized town hall in Bay Ridge|publisher=Brooklynreporter.com|date=2017-04-12|accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bklyner.com/sparks-fly-across-aisle-bay-ridge-hosts-town-hall-lieu-congressman|title=Sparks Fly Across The Aisle As Bay Ridge Hosts Town Hall In Lieu Of Congressman|first=Carly|last=Miller|date=April 21, 2017|publisher=bklyner.com|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Political positions===\nAs of January 2018, Donovan had voted with his party in 91.6% of votes so far in the [[115th United States Congress]] and voted in line with President Trump's position in 81.4% of votes.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/daniel-m-donovan-jr/|title=Tracking Daniel M. Donovan Jr. In The Age Of Trump|date=2017-01-30|work=FiveThirtyEight|access-date=2017-04-22|last=Bycoffe|first=Aaron}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://projects.propublica.org/represent/members/D000625-daniel-m-donovan-jr|title=Represent|work=ProPublica|access-date=2017-04-22}}</ref> Donovan was ranked as the 15th most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives during the [[114th United States Congress]] in the Bipartisan Index created by [[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]] and the [[McCourt School of Public Policy]].<ref>{{Citation|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|date=March 7, 2016|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|publisher=[[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]]|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDonovan has been characterized as a \"moderate Republican\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/albany/story/2018/06/01/grimm-makes-first-ad-buy-against-trump-backed-donovan-as-race-tightens-446108|title=Grimm makes first ad buy against Trump-backed Donovan as race tightens|work=Politico PRO|access-date=2018-06-24|language=en}}</ref> In his  2018 primary election, Donovan ran with an emphasis on conservatism and loyalty to President Trump.<ref name=\":3\"/> In the first session of the [[115th United States Congress]], Donovan's Bipartisan Index rank fell to 50th.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/Senate%20Scores%20115th%20Congress%20First%20Session.pdf|publisher=The Lugar Center|title=McCourt School Bipartisan Index|date=April 24, 2018|access-date=July 3, 2018|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\n====Vote Smart Political Courage Test====\n[[Project Vote Smart|Vote Smart]], a non-profit, non-partisan research organization that collects and distributes information on candidates for public office in the United States, \"researched presidential and congressional candidates' public records to determine candidates' likely responses on certain key issues.\" According to Vote Smart's 2016 analysis, Donovan generally supports pro-choice legislation, opposes federal spending and supports lowering taxes as a means of promoting economic growth, supports the building of the [[Keystone Pipeline]], opposes government funding for the development of renewable energy, opposes the federal regulation of greenhouse gas emissions, supports gun-control legislation, opposes repealing the [[Affordable Care Act]], supports requiring immigrants who are unlawfully present to return to their country of origin before they are eligible for citizenship, opposes same-sex marriage, supports increased American intervention in [[Iraq]] and [[Syria]] beyond air support, and opposes allowing individuals to divert a portion of their [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] taxes into personal retirement accounts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dan Donovan's Issue Positions (Political Courage Test)|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/127760/dan-donovan-jr/#.Wla0EUtG0js|publisher=[[Vote Smart]]|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Donald Trump====\nDonovan endorsed Trump in the 2016 presidential election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://observer.com/2016/07/nyc-gop-rep-new-york-values-are-a-little-bit-more-loyal-than-ted-cruzs-values/|title=NYC GOP Rep: \u2018New York Values Are a Little Bit More Loyal Than Ted Cruz\u2019s Values\u2019|date=2016-07-21|work=Observer|access-date=2018-04-05|language=en-US}}</ref> He has called Trump a \"personal friend\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://observer.com/2015/08/gop-congressman-donald-trump-resonating-with-voters/|title=GOP Congressman: Donald Trump \u2018Resonating With Voters\u2019|date=2015-08-27|work=Observer|access-date=2018-04-05|language=en-US}}</ref> Trump endorsed Donovan's 2018 re-election bid, but in the announcement of his endorsement mistakenly claimed that Donovan had voted for the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/05/30/trump-endorses-rep-donovan-saying-he-voted-tax-bill-he-didnt/658326002/|title=Trump endorses Rep. Dan Donovan who he mistakenly says voted for tax bill|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-05-31|language=en}}</ref> Donovan introduced legislation that would require post offices to display Trump's portrait.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n====Health care====\nIn January 2016, Donovan voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/news/staten-islands-republican-congressman-suddenly-not-so-eager-to-repeal-obamacare-9735031|title=Staten Island's Republican Congressman Suddenly Not So Eager to Repeal Obamacare|last=Barkan|first=Ross|date=2017-03-03|work=Village Voice|access-date=2017-04-22}}</ref> In May 2017, he voted against the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]] (the GOP's bill repealing Obamacare).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.silive.com/news/2017/05/rep_dan_donovan_ahca_is_simply.html|title=Rep. Dan Donovan: GOP health care bill 'simply unfair' to NYC|last=Shapiro|first=Rachel|date=2017-05-04|work=SILive.com|access-date=2018-01-07}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration====\nNew York City's sole Republican member of Congress, Donovan supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to impose a ban on immigration from seven Muslim-majority countries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2017/01/new-yorks-lone-gop-congressman-backs-trump-exec-order-on-immigration-109141|title=New York City's lone GOP congressman backs Trump's executive order|work=Politico PRO|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref> He said, \"President Trump's decision is in America's best interest, and I support exploring safe zones in the region to protect innocent life.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite news |last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump's travel ban; here\u2019s where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban|newspaper=Denver Post|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref> Protesters disrupted a Brooklyn Chamber of Commerce event in February 2017, repeatedly shouting down Donovan due to his support of Trump's immigration ban.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gothamist.com/2017/02/06/dan_donovan_bay_ridge_protest.php|title='You Don't Represent Us': Bay Ridge Congressman Targeted By Protesters At Chamber of Commerce Forum|work=Gothamist|access-date=2017-03-05|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621081950/http://gothamist.com/2017/02/06/dan_donovan_bay_ridge_protest.php|archivedate=June 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Donovan voted in favor of Kate's Law, which would increase penalties for undocumented immigrants that return to the United States after being deported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://donovan.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/donovan-votes-kate-s-law-enhancing-penalties-deported-felons-who-return|title=Donovan Votes for \"Kate\u2019s Law,\" Enhancing Penalties for Deported Felons Who Return to U.S.|date=June 29, 2017|website=house.gov|accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDonovan opposes [[Sanctuary city|sanctuary cities]] (jurisdictions that have policies in place to limit cooperation with federal immigration enforcement).<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2017/03/sanctuary_city_funding_threatened.html|title=Feds threaten millions in funding cuts to NYC for being 'sanctuary city'|work=SILive.com|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> In March 2017, Donovan said that he opposed efforts to reduce funding for jurisdictions with sanctuary policies in place.<ref name=\":1\"/> In April 2018, Donovan introduced legislation that would reduce federal funding to jurisdictions with sanctuary policies in place, such as New York City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2018/04/rep_donovan_to_introduce_bill.html|title=Rep. Donovan to introduce bill punishing 'sanctuary cities'|work=SILive.com|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> In June 2018, Donovan defended the decision of ICE to arrest an undocumented immigrant while delivering a pizza to a Brooklyn Army base.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2018/06/protestors_push_rep_dan_donova.html|title=Protestors push Rep. Dan Donovan on separating families|work=SILive.com|access-date=2018-06-11}}</ref> Amid a 2018 primary challenge, Donovan came out in favor of Trump's wall on the Mexican border, saying \"Build that wall! Build that damn wall!\"<ref name=\":3\"/>\n\n====Cybersecurity====\n\nIn September 2018, Donovan co-sponsored, together with [[Elise Stefanik]] and [[Seth Moulton]], the \"Cyber Ready Workforce Act\" advanced by [[Jacky Rosen]]. The legislation would create a grant program within the [[United States Department of Labor|Department of Labor]] to \"create, implement and expand registered apprenticeships\" in [[cybersecurity]]. It aims to offer certifications and connect participants with businesses in order to \"boost the number\" workers for federal jobs in said trade.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thomsen |first1=Jacqueline |title=Dem introduces bill to create federal cybersecurity apprenticeship program |url=https://thehill.com/policy/cybersecurity/406577-dem-introduces-bill-to-create-federal-cybersecurity-apprenticeship |website=The Hill |accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n====LGBT rights====\nHe was endorsed by the [[Log Cabin Republicans]] in his political career.<ref>{{cite web|title=Donovan Gets Backing Of Log Cabin Republicans|url=http://www.nystateofpolitics.com/2010/08/donovan-gets-backing-of-log-cabin-republicans|publisher=www.nystateofpolitics.com}}</ref> He has been criticized by the Democratic Party for his opposition to same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nystateofpolitics.com/2010/08/lgbt-leaders-gang-up-on-donovan-on-gay-marriage|title=LGBT Leaders Gang Up on Donovan on Gay Marriage|publisher=www.nystateofpolitics.com|access-date=2017-04-22}}</ref> Donovan has a 64% rating from the [[Human Rights Campaign]] based on his LGBT rights-focused voting record.<ref name=\"HRC\">{{cite web|title=114th Congressional Scorecard|url=https://assets2.hrc.org/files/assets/resources/114thCongressionalScorecard.pdf|publisher=Human Rights Campaign|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=January 2018}}\n\n====Marijuana====\nDonovan has a \"C\" rating from [[NORML]] regarding his voting record on [[cannabis]]-related matters. He has voted against allowing veterans access to [[medical marijuana]], if legal in their state, per their Veterans Health Administration doctor's recommendation.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=Working to Reform Marijuana Laws|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/new-york|publisher=NORML||accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Taxes====\nDonovan voted against the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]], one of five New York Republican representatives to do so.<ref name=\"Almukhtar122117\">{{cite news|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=December 21, 2017|date=December 19, 2017}}</ref> In a statement, he shared that he opposed the bill because it would raise taxes for his constituents and additionally impact the \"already unaffordable housing market in my district\".<ref name=\"Segers122017\">{{cite web|last1=Segers|first1=Grace|title=Comparing GOP lawmakers' statements on the tax plan|url=https://www.cityandstateny.com/articles/politics/new-york-state/comparing-gop-lawmakers%E2%80%99-statements-tax-plan.html|publisher=City & State New York|accessdate=December 21, 2017}}</ref> With the [[House Ways and Means Committee]] being scheduled to consider legislation in September 2018 that would make permanent individual tax changes in Trump's 2017 tax law, Donovan stated he would be \"forced to oppose\" more tax cuts if legislation included a provision \"permanently extending the $10,000 cap on the state and local tax (SALT) deduction\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jagoda |first1=Naomi |title=Blue-state Republicans say they will vote against 'tax cuts 2.0' if it extends SALT cap |url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/406238-blue-state-republicans-say-they-will-vote-against-tax-cuts-20-if-it-cements |website=The Hill |accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Unmasking Antifa Act of 2018====\nIn 2018, Donovan introduced a bill that would penalize those who carry out actions that cause \"injury, opposes, threatens or intimidates any person\" while wearing a mask, with the maximum penalty being a 15 year sentence. The legislation, which made reference to the far-left group [[Antifa (United States)|Antifa]], was given media attention after being promoted by [[alt-right]] activist [[Mike Cernovich]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/396404-unmasking-antifa-act-includes-15-year-prison-term-proposal|title=\u2018Unmasking Antifa Act' includes 15-year prison term proposal|last=Birnbaum|first=Emily|date=2018-07-10|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en}}</ref> Professor Mark Bray of Dartmouth said  \"It's a law that threatens to clamp down on direct action politics more broadly, I think it sets a disturbing precedent.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/bjb8kw/antifa-activists-are-freaking-out-about-a-proposed-unmasking-law|title=Antifa Activists Are Freaking Out About a Proposed 'Unmasking' Law|date=2018-07-10|work=Vice|access-date=2018-07-11|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://donovan.house.gov Congressman Dan Donovan] official U.S. House website\n*[http://www.dandonovanforcongress.com/ Dan Donovan for Congress] official campaign website\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Dan_Donovan_%5BR-11%5D|Dan Donovan}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = D000625 | fec = H6NY11174 | votesmart = 127760| congress = daniel-donovan/D000625}}\n*{{C-SPAN|danieldonovan}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Staten Island|Deputy Borough President of Staten Island]]|before=[[James Molinaro]]|years=2002 \u2013 2003|after=[[Edward Burke (Staten Island)|Edward Burke]] }}\n{{S-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William L. Murphy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[District Attorney of Richmond County (New York)|District Attorney of Richmond County]]|years=January 1, 2004 \u2013 May 12, 2015}}\n{{s-aft|after= Daniel L. Master, Jr.|as=Acting}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| before=[[Michael Grimm (politician)|Michael Grimm]]\n| state=New York\n| district=11\n| start=May 5, 2015}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lee Zeldin]]<br>R-[[New York (state)|New York]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=362nd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Trent Kelly]]<br>R-[[Mississippi]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=[[New York Attorney General elections|Republican Nominee for Attorney General of New York]]|before=[[Jeanine Pirro]]|after=[[John P. Cahill]]|years=2010}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{NY-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{Members of the U.S. House of Representatives from New York}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donovan, Dan}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Catholics from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:County district attorneys in New Y